x4freetext: Slow neutron velocity spectrometer.
A burst of neutrons is produced at the source
between t=0 and t=tau, and these neutrons are
detected 6.2 meters from the source between t=t, and
t=t+tau to define the neutron energy in terms of its
time of flight t, over the measured path length.
Sixteen adjacent timing intervals are measured
simultaneously for each of two independent detectors,
thus 32 measurements are made simultaneously. The
detection intervals are spaced in time an amount tau
equal to the width of the individual intervals.

x4freetext: No details on sources of uncertainties.
Compiler`s comment: Energy scale is confusing, so
plots were digitized vs. neutron time of flight in
microsec/meter and converted to energy using the
relation E = (72.3/t) **2 eV which gives the neutron
energy for a timing t, microsec/meter. Transmission
data are more reliable, while cross section scale is
less obvious.
Translated from SCISRS.
Converted to reaction formalism
BP: Digitized all plots and target
materials, added method, sample thicknesses and
resonance parameters. Updated to new date formats,
lower case. corrections according last EXFOR rules
and Dict.
The slow neutron transmission of tungsten was studied
using rolled tungsten plates supplied by the General
Electric Company, Cleveland Wire Works: 29.2 g/cm2. A
spectrographic analysis of the sample showed less
than 1 percent As; 0.5 percent Bi; 0.05 percent Zr, V,
Zn, Cd, and Si; 0.005 percent Be, Fe, Pd, Au, Ge;
traces of La, Ru, Rh, Cu, Hg, Al, Tl, Sn, Pb. For all
other metals the prominent lines were not apparent.
The cross section, sigma, is related to the
transmission, T, by the relation T=exp(-n sigma)
where n=atoms/cm2 of the element studied (if only the
element is present).
Fig. 6, page 169.
BP: replaced the BNL-325 read data.

(4.5 percent) and In115 (95.5 percent). In114
results from the capture of a neutron by In113 which
has a half-life of 48 days. The 13-sec. and 54-min.
In116 are isomers.
